# 🧭 Master Project Index & Router

Use shorthand triggers to load specific project rule modules.

### 🧩 Command & Context Mapping
When I use a trigger, your **FIRST STEP** must be to use the `read_file` tool to load the associated documentation before proceeding with any code changes.

| Trigger | Target File | Scope of Work |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **!prd** | `.cline/docs/PRD.md` | Product requirements, features, and MVP goals. |
| **!arch** | `.cline/docs/architecture.md` | System design, Docker config, and infrastructure. |
| **!back** | `.cline/docs/backend.md` | API logic, Laravel patterns, and service layer. |
| **!front** | `.cline/docs/frontend.md` | Next.js SPA, React components, and state. |
| **!auth** | `.cline/docs/auth.md` | Keycloak, OIDC, PKCE flows, and security protocols. |
| **!db** | `.cline/docs/databases.md` | PostgresSQL/MongoDB schemas and data modeling. |
| **!task** | `.cline/docs/tasks.md` | Current sprint, backlog, issues/tasks/cards and "Definition of Done." |

### 🛠 Operational Rules
1. **Lazy Loading:** Do not attempt to read all sub-files at once. Only load the specific file(s) requested by the trigger.
2. **Context Persistence:** Once a file is read, assume its rules apply until the end of the current task.
3. **Cross-Reference:** If a task in `!back` requires authentication, you may proactively ask to read `!auth`.